[src:ws-websocket/websocket] A secure version of the WebSocket protocol is implemented in Firefox 6, Safari 6, Google Chrome 14, Opera 12.10 and Internet Explorer 10.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] A detailed protocol test suite report lists the conformance of those browsers to specific protocol aspects.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] An older, less secure version of the protocol was implemented in Opera 11 and Safari 5, as well as the mobile version of Safari in iOS 4.2.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] The BlackBerry Browser in OS7 implements WebSockets.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] Because of vulnerabilities, it was disabled in Firefox 4 and 5, and Opera 11.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] Using browser developer tools, developers can inspect the WebSocket handshake as well as the WebSocket frames.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] ASP.NET Core have support for WebSockets using the `app.UseWebSockets();` middleware.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] Unlike regular cross-domain HTTP requests, WebSocket requests are not restricted by the same-origin policy.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] It is better to use tokens or similar protection mechanisms to authenticate the WebSocket connection when sensitive (private) data is being transferred over the WebSocket.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] A live example of vulnerability was seen in 2020 in the form of Cable Haunt.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] WebSocket protocol client implementations try to detect whether the user agent is configured to use a proxy when connecting to destination host and port, and if it is, uses HTTP CONNECT method to set up a persistent tunnel.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] The WebSocket protocol is unaware of proxy servers and firewalls.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] Some proxy servers are transparent and work fine with WebSocket; others will prevent WebSocket from working correctly, causing the connection to fail.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] In some cases, additional proxy-server configuration may be required, and certain proxy servers may need to be upgraded to support WebSocket.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] If unencrypted WebSocket traffic flows through an explicit or a transparent proxy server without WebSockets support, the connection will likely fail.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] If an encrypted WebSocket connection is used, then the use of Transport Layer Security (TLS) in the WebSocket Secure connection ensures that an `HTTP CONNECT` command is issued when the browser is configured to use an explicit proxy server.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] This sets up a tunnel, which provides low-level end-to-end TCP communication through the HTTP proxy, between the WebSocket Secure client and the WebSocket server.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] In the case of transparent proxy servers, the browser is unaware of the proxy server, so no `HTTP CONNECT` is sent.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] However, since the wire traffic is encrypted, intermediate transparent proxy servers may simply allow the encrypted traffic through, so there is a much better chance that the WebSocket connection will succeed if WebSocket Secure is used.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] Using encryption is not free of resource cost, but often provides the highest success rate, since it would be travelling through a secure tunnel.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] A mid-2010 draft (version hixie-76) broke compatibility with reverse proxies and gateways by including eight bytes of key data after the headers, but not advertising that data in a `Content-Length: 8` header.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] This data was not forwarded by all intermediates, which could lead to protocol failure.
[src:ws-websocket/websocket] More recent drafts (e.g., hybi-09) put the key data in a `Sec-WebSocket-Key` header, solving this problem.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] The **WebSocket API** makes it possible to open a two-way interactive communication session between the user's browser and a server.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] With this API, you can send messages to a server and receive responses without having to poll the server for a reply.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] The WebSocket API provides two alternative mechanisms for creating and using web socket connections: the `WebSocket` interface and the `WebSocketStream` interface.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] Additionally, the WebTransport API is expected to replace the WebSocket API for many applications.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] WebTransport is a versatile, low-level API that provides backpressure and many other features not supported by either `WebSocket` or `WebSocketStream`, such as unidirectional streams, out-of-order delivery, and unreliable data transmission via datagrams.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] WebTransport is more complex to use than WebSockets and its cross-browser support is not as wide, but it enables the implementation of sophisticated solutions.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] If standard WebSocket connections are a good fit for your use case and you need wide browser compatibility, you should employ the WebSockets API to get up and running quickly.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] However, if your application requires a non-standard custom solution, then you should use the WebTransport API.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] The primary interface for connecting to a WebSocket server and then sending and receiving data on the connection.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] Promise-based interface for connecting to a WebSocket server; uses streams to send and receive data on the connection.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] The event sent by the WebSocket object when the connection closes.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] The event sent by the WebSocket object when a message is received from the server.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] An HTTP request header that contains a nonce from the client.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] This is used in the WebSocket opening handshake to verify that the client explicitly intends to open a WebSocket.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] It is added automatically by the browser.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] An HTTP response header used in the *WebSocket opening handshake* to indicate that the server is willing to upgrade to a WebSocket connection.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] The value in the directive is calculated from the value of `Sec-WebSocket-Key` in the corresponding request.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] An HTTP header that in requests indicates the version of the WebSocket protocol understood by the client.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] In responses, it is sent only if the requested protocol version is not supported by the server, and lists the versions that the server supports.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] An HTTP header that in requests indicates the sub-protocols supported by the client in preferred order.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] In responses, it indicates the sub-protocol selected by the server from the client's preferences.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] An HTTP header that in requests indicates the WebSocket extensions supported by the client in preferred order.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-api] In responses, it indicates the extension selected by the server from the client's preferences.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] ws is a simple to use, blazing fast, and thoroughly tested WebSocket client and server implementation.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] Passes the quite extensive Autobahn test suite: server, client.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] This is a binary addon that improves the performance of certain operations such as masking and unmasking the data payload of the WebSocket frames.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] Prebuilt binaries are available for the most popular platforms, so you don't necessarily need to have a C++ compiler installed on your machine.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] To force ws to not use bufferutil, use the `WS_NO_BUFFER_UTIL` environment variable.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] This can be useful to enhance security in systems where a user can put a package in the package search path of an application of another user, due to how the Node.js resolver algorithm works.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] This contains a binary polyfill for `buffer.isUtf8()`.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] To force ws not to use utf-8-validate, use the `WS_NO_UTF_8_VALIDATE` environment variable.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] See `/doc/ws.md` for Node.js-like documentation of ws classes and utility functions.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] ws supports the permessage-deflate extension which enables the client and server to negotiate a compression algorithm and its parameters, and then selectively apply it to the data payloads of each WebSocket message.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] The extension is disabled by default on the server and enabled by default on the client.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] It adds a significant overhead in terms of performance and memory consumption so we suggest to enable it only if it is really needed.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] Note that Node.js has a variety of issues with high-performance compression, where increased concurrency, especially on Linux, can lead to catastrophic memory fragmentation and slow performance.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] If you intend to use permessage-deflate in production, it is worthwhile to set up a test representative of your workload and ensure Node.js/zlib will handle it with acceptable performance and memory usage.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] Tuning of permessage-deflate can be done via the options defined below.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] You can also use `zlibDeflateOptions` and `zlibInflateOptions`, which is passed directly into the creation of raw deflate/inflate streams.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] The client will only use the extension if it is supported and enabled on the server.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] To always disable the extension on the client, set the `perMessageDeflate` option to `false`.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] Also see the provided example using `express-session`.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] A client WebSocket broadcasting to all connected WebSocket clients, including itself.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] A client WebSocket broadcasting to every other connected WebSocket clients, excluding itself.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] For a full example with a browser client communicating with a ws server, see the examples folder.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] The remote IP address can be obtained from the raw socket.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] When the server runs behind a proxy like NGINX, the de-facto standard is to use the `X-Forwarded-For` header.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] Sometimes, the link between the server and the client can be interrupted in a way that keeps both the server and the client unaware of the broken state of the connection (e.g. when pulling the cord).
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] In these cases, ping messages can be used as a means to verify that the remote endpoint is still responsive.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] Pong messages are automatically sent in response to ping messages as required by the spec.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] Just like the server example above, your clients might as well lose connection without knowing it.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] You might want to add a ping listener on your clients to prevent that.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] Use a custom `http.Agent` implementation like https-proxy-agent or socks-proxy-agent.
[src:ws-websocket/websockets-ws] We're using the GitHub releases for changelog entries.
